We can see that the forecasts are pretty good on average!

Considering the two points from before:

  1. The mean and variance of the measures (and forecats) are definitely increasing. This is not surprising due to the consistent progression of the wind generation industry (growth in number of wind farms and better turbines).
  2. It seems there is a weak seasonal pattern, lets look into it:

It looks like there is nothing distinct, but carefully one can point to a better result of the MDA method when the wind generation is strong (around morning and Spring), and on contrary when the wind generation is weak (evening and Autumn).

It is worth doing a statistical hypothesis testing for checking if the two methods are significantly different statistically. Due to the large size of the samples it is fine to assume that the errors (or the forecasts, it's the same) are normally distributed (it's also easy to see that from the graph). I executed a t-test, and as it possible to see from the very high p-value, we can't reject the null hypothesis (with a good significance level) that these two columns have the same mean (and indeed the averages of these two are very close, and small comparing to the variance).

In [70]:
stats.ttest_ind(united['Error_ECM'],united['Error_MDA'],equal_var = False)
Out[70]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=0.38692573063026137, pvalue=0.6988119881368282)

So for conclusion, in my opinion, it's not really appropriate to point at one of the methods as better. The ECM error is a bit more centered, the MDA error has a bit smaller mean and variance, but overall, the two methods are similar and about the same quality.

I would say that both methods are sufficiently accurate and the criterion for chossing between them should be a matter of costs (i.e., which is easyer/cheaper/faster to produce), comfort or other domains.

However, I've tried to construct a robust function that ignores our specific situation and can recieve as input any DataFrame of three columns (that are timestamp, true values and predictions), as well as a time period, and returns a column with the compatible rolling MAE values (but can very easily be changed to any other evaluation metric).

In [73]:
from sklearn import metrics
In [74]:
def rolling_MAE (df, time_period, num_period = 1):
    """ Inputs:
        df = A DataFrame with a time series, actual measures series and forecasts series.
        time_period = 'hour', 'day', 'week' or 'month'. Any other input will raise an error.
        num_period = Number (a positive integer) of time_period units to consider while computing the rolling value of the MAE.
        Output:
        Plot of the rolling value of the MAE according to the time series of the input.
        Remarks:
        Using the 'mean_absolute_error' function from the 'sklearn.metrics' library.
        Can be easily modified to a different evaluation metric (see the remark in the function body)
    """
    if type(num_period) != int or num_period <= 0:
        raise ValueError('num_period must be a positive integer')
    if time_period == 'hour':
        chunk_size = num_period
    elif time_period == 'day':
        chunk_size = 24*num_period
    elif time_period == 'week':
        chunk_size = 24*7*num_period
    elif time_period == 'month':
        chunk_size = 24*30*num_period
    else:
        raise ValueError('time_period must be "hour", "day", "week" or "month".')
    real = df.columns.values[0]
    forecast = df.columns.values[1]
    # For changing the evaluation metric: replace 'mean_absolute_error' in the next line by another regression metric form sklearn.metrics.
    df['rolling_MAE'] = np.concatenate((np.zeros(chunk_size), np.array([metrics.mean_absolute_error(df[real].iloc[(i-chunk_size):i], df[forecast].iloc[(i-chunk_size):i]) for i in range(chunk_size,len(df))])),axis = 0)
    sns.lineplot(data = df['rolling_MAE'], label='rolling MAE ({} {}s)'.format(num_period, time_period))

Usually a rolling average is used to see trends(/cycles) or to smooth a "rocking" graph. I find it less beneficial to look at the evalutaion metric trend in this case. Do we expect our forecasting method's quality to change with time? However, it helps with the smoothing of our really fluctuating graphs...

In this case, the graph of the rolling value is much smoother than the weekly average and it easier too see the cyclic trend, when the rolling MAE grows to a peak in the Winter and then decreases to a low in the Summer, and furthermore, there is an increase in this value during the years.
